Dataframe to pandas and to RDD.

There are three escape hatches you should know for stepping outside the dataframe interface.

The first is to pandas. It pulls every single row into one pandas dataframe sitting on the driver. That is genuinely convenient for plotting and final-mile analysis. But it is dangerous on large data — it can run the driver out of memory. So always sample or aggregate first. The same trap exists on the Spark side with collect, which we cover in the performance notebook.

The second hatch is the reverse direction: create dataframe handed a pandas dataframe distributes it back across the cluster. That one is useful for tiny test fixtures.

The third is dot rdd, which drops you down to an RDD of row objects. You reach for this when you genuinely need an RDD-only operation, like map partitions. And the round-trip back is to-D-F, which lifts the RDD up into a dataframe again with a schema.
